content.text: When it comes to taking care of your health, small changes may lead to big improvements. We'll help you learn how to better manage your health using skills that you can master through achievable action steps. You can take control of your health to help you live the life you want.

content.text: One key to living well with a health condition is having good self-management skills. There are three main skills needed for effective self-management. Using the scale below as a guide, how do you feel you’ve done with the following:

choice.text: I've consistently done a great job.
I've consistently done a pretty good job.
I've consistently had a hard time.
I had a hard time at first, but it continues to get easier.
I started out doing well, but it's been getting harder.
I haven't been able to manage my condition(s) consistently.

content.text: In general, how do you feel you've been doing with managing your health condition(s)?
How many different medications are you supposed to take each day?
Are you:
And would you say that in general your quality of life is:

With any health condition, there are a lot of things to remember and do. It can seem like a lot of work to make things better. Research shows that good self management of chronic conditions can help improve one's overall health. What skills can you use to improve your health?

choice.text: I’m afraid of my health issues.
I find it really hard to accept that I have health issues.
I’m pretty fortunate, all things considered.
I feel unhappy and depressed because of my health issues.
I miss the person I used to be.
Living with my health issues has made me a stronger person.
I worry about my future health.
I can do just about anything I set out to do.
Even if I can't be cured, I can manage my health issues.
It isn’t fair that I have my health issues.
I get stressed thinking about everything I have to do to care for my health.
My health can be improved if I take control of it. Ultimately, it’s up to me.

Stress is a normal part of life, but knowing how to relax can help you deal with it. Your Learning to Relax skill will teach you some techniques that you can use when you start to feel your stress building.
You aren't alone when it comes to taking care of your health. There's a team of people including your health care providers and important people in your life who are there to support you.

Most doctor visits last only 15 minutes. That's not a lot of time to cover everything, especially important information and questions. Having a good relationship and being comfortable talking with your doctor can help you take control of your health.

content.text: In general, how satisfied are you with the support you get from your family and friends?

Having people in your corner can make managing your health a little easier. Another source of support is your health care team. Their job is to help you; your job is to use your limited time with them as well as possible to ask questions and discuss problems. We’ll talk about some helpful strategies in your Coordinating Care skill.
Ready to turn to what’s really driving you?

We know that you want to take care of your condition because of its impact on your life. We want to help you build the motivation you’ll need for the long run. Let’s dive a little deeper to better understand a bit more about what’s important to you.
First of all, how motivated are you to manage your health?

How confident are you that you can do it?

To take care of my family.

content.text: There are many reasons why you may want to stay as healthy as possible. We know it can be hard to choose just one, but which of the following is most important to you?

choice.text: ACCOMPLISHMENT - mastery of knowledge, skills, abilities
ADVENTURE - seeking big rewards from big risks
BALANCE - inner peace, centered, moderate, perspective
COMMUNITY - participating in groups that share your neighborhood, type of work, or beliefs
COURAGE - testing limits, facing difficulties with resilience
CREATIVITY - imagination, new ways of doing and seeing
FUN - enjoyment, playfulness, sense of play
GENEROSITY - sharing time, money, and energy with others
GROWTH - forward motion in personal development
INTEGRITY - honesty, strength of character, and justice in dealings with others
RELATIONSHIPS - strong, active bonds with family and friends
RESPECT - fair treatment, valuing individuals for uniqueness
SPIRITUALITY - connection with something larger than the "here and now"
SERVICE - to be of assistance and support to a person or cause

content.text: We'd like to ask you about something that might surprise you – what drives you? It's important to tie changes in your life to the things that are most important to you. So what do you consider to be your "core values?" Please choose the three that mean the most to you and that define you as a person.

choice.text: I do my best to keep the commitments I make.
I believe that hard work can bring success.
When I put my mind to it, I can do just about anything.
When I start something, I almost always stick with it.
I’m really good at starting things, but I often fizzle out.
I’m not a big planner; I just try to do what works.

content.text: Which of the following statements are true for you?

When it comes to managing your health, your values play an important role. In your Building Motivation skill, you’ll see how focusing on what is important in your life can be just what you need to keep you on track with caring for your health.

Now, we'd like to learn a bit about how much physical activity you're getting.

During moderate-intensity activities, you’re able to hold a conversation, but you’re working hard enough to raise your heart rate and break a sweat. Brisk walking, casual swimming and doubles tennis are examples of moderate-intensity activities.

childQuestions.text: day(s)

content.text: In a typical week, what is the average amount of time you spend doing moderate-intensity physical activity?

During vigorous-intensity activities, you’re breathing hard and fast, and your heart rate has gone up quite a bit. If you’re working at this level, you won’t be able to say more than a few words without pausing for a breath. These types of activities include running, bicycling, swimming laps, and weight circuit training.

Think about the days you were limited in the amount or kind of work you could do. For example, days you accomplished less than you would have liked, or days you couldn't do your work as carefully as usual. If health problems affected your work only a little, choose a low number. content.text: During the past 4 weeks, how much did your health problems affect your productivity while you were working?

We’re going to ask you to think about how your health problems affect your ability to do your regular daily activities. By regular activities, we mean activities like work around the house, shopping, child care, exercising, studying, etc. Think about times you were limited in the amount or kind of activities you could do and times you accomplished less than you would like. If health problems affected your activities only a little, choose a low number. Choose a high number if health problems affected your activities a lot.
